diff:1620528552:1620526386:=53,71c53%0a%3c #foxbegin 210509-024912-651180#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Filler words in Mandarin and its unfortunate pronunciation %0a%3c -> - Simon_Y%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c Just wanted to add an example of a filler word in Mandarin.%0a%3c %0a%3c "那个" is a filler word in Mandarin, roughly translate to "that". It is pronunced as nàge/nèige in Pinyin, and [nagə] or [negə]. As you may have heard of or realized now, this can be misheard into an undesirable English word.%0a%3c %0a%3c An unfortunate incidence has occured: https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2020/09/08/professor-suspended-saying-chinese-word-sounds-english-slur%0a%3c This case actually reveals a bigger problem than an incident, as the faculty was suspended. I agree that the speaker should apologize for the incident and clarify that it was unintentional. I would argue that the usage of filler words, as the article points out, is subconscious. Mutual understanding is crucial when building a diverse community, which was not present in this incident.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ref:%0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Filler_(linguistics)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210509-024912-651180#%0a---%0a> %0a
